    <h1>Energy Crops</h1>
	
	<table align="right" style="background-color: #003c23; " cellspacing="0">
	<tr><td><img src="../Photos/EnergyGrass.jpg" alt="Energy grass"></td></tr>
	<tr><td align="center" style="color:#FFFFFF; "><strong>Energy grass</strong></td></tr></table>

	
    
	
    <p><strong>How can we meet our targets for reducing carbon  emissions and give British agriculture a much-needed boost at the same time? </strong></p>
	
    <p><strong>Energy crops that can be converted to &ldquo;carbon  neutral&rdquo; power could be the answer. At Rothamsted Research work to support such  crops ranges from molecular studies to assuring end use suitability for the  energy industry</strong>. <strong>Elspeth Bartlet talks to programme leader  Angela Karp and agronomist Ian Shield.</strong></p>
	
    <p>As part of its efforts to tackle climate  change, the government has already identified a target of increasing generation  from renewable energy sources to 10% by 2010 and is now planning that a fifth  of all electricity be generated by renewable energy sources by 2020.&nbsp; Energy crops are seen as an important part of  this renewables target because, unlike fossil fuels, they are &ldquo;carbon-neutral&rdquo;  only releasing on combustion the carbon they took up through photosynthesis  whilst growing. They could also benefit British farmers, who are badly in need  of new crops that can diversify or increase their income. </p>
	
    <p>Short rotation coppice  willow is already being grown as an energy crop in parts of the UK but crop breeding has the potential to greatly  improve yields, making it economically viable for a much wider range of growers.  Rothamsted&rsquo;s research on bioenergy is aimed at helping to bring about these  improvements. Dr Angela Karp&rsquo;s research group on energy crops encompasses a  wide range of disciplines, including molecular genetics, taxonomy, pests,  diseases and agronomy. </p>
	
    <p>Central to the work of this  group is a unique resource; <strong>the National Willows Collection. </strong>This is a repository for willow germplasm,  set up in the 1920s as a way of conserving  varieties which were being lost when rural crafts such as basket and hurdle-making  declined. Today, it is maintained on the Rothamsted farm and contains around 1300 biotypes. This is the source of  genetic variation that Dr Karp&rsquo;s group are tapping into for breeding 
improved coppice  willow.</p>

		<table align="left" style="background-color: #003c23; " cellspacing="0">
	<tr><td><img src="../Photos/willow.jpg" alt="Willow"></td></tr>
	<tr><td align="center" style="color:#FFFFFF; "><strong>Willow</strong></td></tr></table>

    <p>Wander around the collection  and some of this genetic variety is immediately apparent. Bark colour can be red,  yellow green or brown, heights range from less than 1 m to greater than 4 m, and some have straight stems, whilst  others are twisted like sticks of barely sugar. &nbsp;&ldquo;We have to get to grips with the genetic  relationships within the collection if we want to maximise its usefulness,&rdquo; says  Dr Karp. &ldquo;It is essential that we understand the diversity that we have in  there and how best to use it, but it is incredibly complicated because it  contains around 100 of the 400 species in the genus and a huge number of hybrids&rdquo;. </p>
	
    <p>Visiting worker, Dr. Irina  Belyaeva, a specialist in <em>Salix</em> (willow) taxonomy from the Urals Botanic Garden is helping to untangle this puzzle. She is working  with Rothamsted scientist Dr. Sviatlana Trybush, who has been using molecular  techniques to characterise diversity in the collection. Together they are  making a herbarium and conducting a complete morphological and molecular  characterisation in order to resolve taxonomic ambiguities, select  representative reference samples for a core collection and determine genetic  relationships.&nbsp; </p>
	
    <p>&ldquo;Understanding the genetic  basis of important diversity in willow underpins all of our research&rdquo;, says Dr  Karp. As part of the Defra Crop Improvement Network Rothamsted scientist Dr.  Steve Hanley is using genetic mapping and genomic approaches to identify where  the genes conferring yield, disease and pest resistance are located in the  willow genome. This information is being used to help select parents for  crossing and improved progeny in the breeding programme. &nbsp;&ldquo;Our efforts are greatly helped by the whole  genome sequencing of the International Poplar Genome Consortium in the USA. Poplar is very closely related to willow so looking  at the poplar genome will help us to identify genes conferring the important traits  much faster&rdquo;. Collaborators in this network are Dr Gail Taylor at the University of Southampton, Cranfield University and ADAS.</p>
	
    <p>Pest and disease problems could become a real headache  for coppice willow growers. &ldquo;This is because willows are perennial crops so, unlike  cereals or oilseed rape you can&rsquo;t use crop rotations to keep pest and disease  problems down,&rdquo; says agronomist Dr Ian Shield. &ldquo;What&rsquo;s more, they are difficult  crops to apply pesticides in, so pest and disease resistant traits in willow are  really valuable to breeders&rdquo;. Rusts are currently the worst disease problem for  the crop and plant pathologist Dr Ming Pei is looking for integrated control solutions for  coppice willow. One outcome of his work is the recommendation that coppice  willow should be grown in varietal mixtures to reduce disease susceptibility. This  is now recommended practice in the industry.</p>

			<table align="right" style="background-color: #003c23; " cellspacing="0">
	<tr><td><img src="../Photos/Miscanthus.jpg" alt="Miscanthus"></td></tr>
	<tr><td align="center" style="color:#FFFFFF; "><strong>Miscanthus</strong></td></tr></table>
	
    <p>&ldquo;However, coppice willows  aren&rsquo;t the only viable energy crop for the UK,&rdquo; Ian continues. &ldquo;Energy grasses such as <em>Miscanthus</em>, reed canary grass or  switchgrass can produce as much biomass as coppice willow and are suitable for  combustion in straw-burning power stations or in other energy-producing  processes&rdquo;.</p>

	
    <p>Miscanthus and switchgrass  are not native to the UK, so the Dti and Defra &ldquo;Topgrass&rdquo; project led by  Andrew Riche at Rothamsted is studying the performance of all three grasses at  nine sites with varying soil types and climates in order to assess their  commercial potential for growers across the UK. Initial results indicate a wide geographic range  for all three grasses, but that Miscanthus and switchgrass may be a little less  well suited to cooler climates. </p>
	
   <p>Whether growers opt for coppice  willow or energy grasses, their success will, to a large extent, depend on  researchers and breeders producing the right product for the market. To this  end, Rothamsted is a partner in the EPSRC&rsquo;s SUPERGREN project, which brings researchers  and breeders into contact with growers and power providers to ensure that new crop  varieties are tailored to the needs of British agriculture and the energy  industry. Nicola Yates is conducting a series of experiments to test the effect  of agronomic treatments on the quality or suitability of energy grasses for a  number of end uses such as direct combustion, gasification, pyrolosis or  fermentation. For example the application of nitrogen or potassium-containing  fertilisers in excess could decrease their suitability for end users. </p>
   
    <p>Successful development of energy  crops could mean a radical change in the way we produce our power and the way  we manage our countryside. We could be getting a lot more out of willow than  just cricket bats.</p>
	
